              "content": "# Build Settlement Calldata\n\nGuide the user through constructing `Settlement.settle()` calldata from `/solve` API data using the SDK.\n\n**User argument**: $ARGUMENTS (optional: path to a JSON file containing request/response, or \"help\")\n\nIf the argument is \"help\" or empty, explain the full workflow below. If a JSON file path is provided, read the file and use its data to generate concrete code.\n\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nThe core data flow is:\n\n```\nSolveRequest + SolveResponse → buildSettleCalldata() → hex calldata → Settlement.settle()\n```\n\nThe SDK function `buildSettleCalldata()` handles all the heavy lifting:\n- Collecting unique token addresses\n- Converting decimal string prices to `bigint`\n- Building `Trade[]` with packed flag bitmasks\n- Sorting trades by `toTokenAddressIndex` (contract requirement)\n- ABI-encoding the final calldata\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Understand the API Types\n\n### SolveRequest (from `/solve` request body)\n\n```typescript\ninterface SolveRequest {\n  auctionId: string;           // becomes settleId (bigint)\n  orders: SolveRequestOrder[];\n}\n\ninterface SolveRequestOrder {\n  fromTokenAddress: string;\n  toTokenAddress: string;\n  owner: string;\n  receiver: string;\n  fromTokenAmount: string;     // decimal string\n  toTokenAmount: string;       // decimal string (minimum)\n  validTo: number;             // unix timestamp (seconds)\n  appDataHash: string;         // bytes32 hex\n  swapMode: string;            // \"exactIn\" | \"exactOut\"\n  partiallyFillable: boolean;\n  signingScheme: string;       // \"eip712\" | \"ethSign\" | \"eip1271\" | \"preSign\"\n  signature: string;           // hex\n  commissionInfos: ApiCommissionInfo[];\n}\n```\n\n### SolveResponse (from `/solve` response body)\n\n```typescript\ninterface SolveResponse {\n  solutions: Solution[];       // typically 1 solution\n}\n\ninterface Solution {\n  clearingPrices: Record\u003cstring, string\u003e;  // lowercase token address → decimal string\n  orders: SolveResponseOrder[];            // parallel to request.orders\n  surplusFeeInfo: ApiSurplusFeeInfo;\n}\n\ninterface SolveResponseOrder {\n  executedFromTokenAmount: string;   // decimal string\n  executedToTokenAmount: string;     // decimal string\n  commissionInfos: ApiCommissionInfo[];\n  solverFeeInfo: ApiSolverFeeInfo;\n}\n```\n\n### Fee Types\n\n```typescript\ninterface ApiCommissionInfo {\n  feePercent: string;              // 1e9 precision decimal string\n  referrerWalletAddress: string;\n  feeDirection: boolean;           // true = fromToken, false = toToken\n  toB: boolean;                    // true = Settlement pays, false = user pays\n  commissionType: string;          // \"okx\" | \"parent\" | \"child\"\n}\n\ninterface ApiSolverFeeInfo {\n  feePercent: string;\n  solverAddress: string;\n  feeDirection: boolean;\n  feeAmount: string;               // informational, not stored on-chain\n}\n\ninterface ApiSurplusFeeInfo {\n  feePercent: string;\n  trimReceiver: string;\n  flag: string;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Prepare API Data\n\nIf your raw API response has an envelope or extra fields, strip them down to match the types above:\n\n```typescript\n// If your API wraps the response in an envelope:\nconst rawApiResponse = await fetch('/solve', { ... }).then(r =\u003e r.json());\n\n// Extract what the SDK expects:\nconst request: SolveRequest = {\n  auctionId: rawApiResponse.auctionId,\n  orders: rawApiResponse.orders,  // strip extra fields if present\n};\n\nconst response: SolveResponse = {\n  solutions: rawApiResponse.solutions,\n};\n```\n\n**Important**: All numeric amounts are **decimal strings** (not `bigint`). The SDK converts internally.\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Build Interactions (if needed)\n\nInteractions represent on-chain calls executed during settlement in 3 phases:\n\n```typescript\nimport type { Interaction } from '@okx-intent-swap/sdk-common';\n\n// Structure: [pre-swap, swap, post-swap]\n// Most solvers: approve tokens + execute DEX swap in the swap phase\nconst interactions: [Interaction[], Interaction[], Interaction[]] = [\n  [],  // pre-swap: empty\n  [\n    // approve fromToken to DEX router\n    {\n      target: fromTokenAddress,\n      value: 0n,\n      callData: erc20ApproveCalldata,  // approve(router, amount)\n    },\n    // execute DEX swap\n    {\n      target: dexRouterAddress,\n      value: 0n,\n      callData: swapCalldata,\n    },\n  ],\n  [],  // post-swap: empty\n];\n```\n\nIf no interactions are needed, pass `undefined` or `[[], [], []]` (the default).\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Call buildSettleCalldata\n\n```typescript\nimport {\n  buildSettleCalldata,\n  type SolveRequest,\n  type SolveResponse,\n} from '@okx-intent-swap/sdk-solver';\n\nconst result = buildSettleCalldata(request, response, {\n  // interactions: [[], [], []],    // optional, default: no interactions\n  // solutionIndex: 0,              // optional, default: first solution\n  // useComputedPrices: true,       // optional, default: true\n});\n\n// result.calldata  → 0x-prefixed hex string, ready for on-chain tx\n// result.params    → decoded parameters for inspection:\n//   .settleId      → bigint\n//   .tokens        → string[]\n//   .clearingPrices → bigint[]\n//   .trades        → Trade[]\n//   .interactions  → [Interaction[], Interaction[], Interaction[]]\n//   .surplusFeeInfo → { feePercent: bigint, trimReceiver: string, flag: bigint }\n```\n\n### useComputedPrices Option\n\n- **`true` (default)**: Computes clearing prices from execution amounts + fees. This is the recommended mode as it produces deterministic prices that match the contract's fee computation.\n- **`false`**: Uses `solution.clearingPrices` directly (decimal strings → uint256). Only use this if you need exact control over clearing prices.\n\n---\n\n## Step 5: Verify the Output\n\n### Type-check your code\n\n```bash\npnpm build\n# or\nnpx tsc -b packages/common packages/contracts packages/solver\n```\n\n### Round-trip decode ver