              "content": "---\nname: write-brd\ndescription: Generate a Business Requirements Document (BRD) for a project or initiative. Covers business context, problem statement, stakeholders, success metrics, and ROI justification.\nuser-invocable: true\nargument-hint: [project-name-or-description]\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash, Write, Edit\n---\n\n# Write BRD (Business Requirements Document)\n\nGenerate a structured BRD for the project or initiative described in `$ARGUMENTS`.\n\nIf `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, ask the user to describe the project. If a file path is provided, read it for context.\n\n## What is a BRD\n\nBRD = Business Requirements Document. It answers **\"Why does this project exist?\"** from a business perspective. It connects a business problem to a proposed initiative, identifies stakeholders, and defines measurable success criteria.\n\nA BRD is NOT a feature list (that's PRD) or a technical design (that's Spec). It sits **upstream** of both:\n\n```\nBRD (Why) → PRD (What) → Spec (How) → Plan (When)\n```\n\n## Document Structure\n\nGenerate the following sections. Adapt depth to project scope — a 1-week internal tool needs less than a platform migration.\n\n### 1. Executive Summary\n\n- One paragraph: what is being proposed and why\n- Target audience: leadership, non-technical stakeholders\n\n### 2. Business Context\n\n- Current state: how things work today\n- Problem statement: pain points, inefficiencies, risks\n- Market / competitive context (if applicable)\n- Regulatory or compliance drivers (if applicable)\n\n### 3. Business Objectives\n\nConcrete, measurable goals. Use SMART format:\n\n| Objective | Metric | Target | Timeline |\n|-----------|--------|--------|----------|\n| Reduce manual review time | Hours / week | -50% | Q2 2026 |\n| Improve onboarding speed | Days to first contribution | \u003c 3 days | Q3 2026 |\n\n### 4. Stakeholders\n\n| Role | Name / Team | Interest | Impact Level |\n|------|-------------|----------|-------------|\n| Sponsor | ... | Budget, strategic alignment | High |\n| End Users | ... | Daily workflow | High |\n| Engineering | ... | Implementation, maintenance | Medium |\n\n### 5. Scope\n\n**In Scope:**\n- Bullet list of what this initiative covers\n\n**Out of Scope:**\n- Bullet list of what is explicitly excluded (and why)\n\n### 6. Constraints \u0026 Assumptions\n\n- **Constraints**: budget, timeline, regulatory, technology\n- **Assumptions**: things taken as true that could invalidate the plan if wrong\n- **Dependencies**: external teams, services, approvals\n\n### 7. Success Criteria \u0026 ROI\n\n- Quantitative KPIs with measurement method\n- Qualitative benefits\n- Cost-benefit summary (if data available)\n- Risk-adjusted timeline\n\n### 8. Risks\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|-----------|--------|------------|\n| ... | High/Med/Low | High/Med/Low | ... |\n\n### 9. Approval \u0026 Next Steps\n\n- Decision needed: approve / reject / request changes\n- Next phase: PRD → Spec → Plan\n- Timeline for decision\n\n## Quality Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every objective is measurable (has a metric + target)\n- [ ] Scope boundaries are explicit (In/Out clearly stated)\n- [ ] No technical implementation details (those belong in Spec)\n- [ ] Risks have mitigations, not just identification\n- [ ] Stakeholders are identified with impact levels\n- [ ] Language is accessible to non-technical readers\n\n## Style Guidelines\n\n- Write in third person, professional tone\n- Use tables for structured data (objectives, stakeholders, risks)\n- Keep Executive Summary under 200 words\n- Avoid jargon — if a technical term is necessary, define it\n- Use `$ENV_VAR` placeholders for sensitive values (IPs, keys, domains)\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Gather context: read project files, README, existing docs\n2. Ask clarifying questions if business context is unclear\n3. Generate BRD following the structure above\n4. Write to `docs/brd.md` (or path specified by user)\n5. Summarize key points and ask for review\n",
