              "content": "---\nname: write-prd\ndescription: Generate a Product Requirements Document (PRD) for a feature or system. Covers user stories, functional requirements, information architecture, and acceptance criteria.\nuser-invocable: true\nargument-hint: [project-name-or-description]\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash, Write, Edit\n---\n\n# Write PRD (Product Requirements Document)\n\nGenerate a structured PRD for the feature or system described in `$ARGUMENTS`.\n\nIf `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, ask the user to describe the product/feature. If a file path is provided, read it for context. If a BRD exists, reference it.\n\n## What is a PRD\n\nPRD = Product Requirements Document. It answers **\"What are we building?\"** from the product perspective. It translates business objectives (BRD) into user-facing requirements without prescribing technical implementation.\n\n```\nBRD (Why) → PRD (What) → Spec (How) → Plan (When)\n```\n\n## Document Structure\n\n### 1. Overview\n\n- Product / feature name\n- One-paragraph description\n- Link to BRD (if exists)\n- Target users / personas\n\n### 2. Core Concepts\n\nDefine the domain model — the key nouns and their relationships:\n\n```\nConcept A\n  ├── has many: Concept B\n  └── belongs to: Concept C\n```\n\nFor each concept:\n- Definition in one sentence\n- Key attributes\n- Relationship to other concepts\n\n### 3. User Stories \u0026 Scenarios\n\nGroup by persona or capability area:\n\n```\nAs a [role], I want to [action], so that [benefit].\n```\n\nFor complex flows, use scenario format:\n\n```\nScenario: [name]\n  Given [precondition]\n  When [action]\n  Then [expected result]\n```\n\n### 4. Functional Requirements\n\nNumbered list, categorized by feature area:\n\n| ID | Requirement | Priority | Notes |\n|----|------------|----------|-------|\n| FR-01 | System shall ... | Must | ... |\n| FR-02 | System shall ... | Should | ... |\n| FR-03 | System may ... | Could | ... |\n\nPriority levels (MoSCoW):\n- **Must**: launch blocker\n- **Should**: important but not blocking\n- **Could**: nice to have\n- **Won't**: explicitly deferred\n\n### 5. Information Architecture\n\n- Data model / entity relationships\n- State machines (if applicable)\n- Key workflows / decision trees\n\nUse text diagrams:\n\n```\n[State A] --event--\u003e [State B] --event--\u003e [State C]\n```\n\n### 6. Non-Functional Requirements\n\n| Category | Requirement | Target |\n|----------|------------|--------|\n| Performance | Response time | \u003c 200ms p95 |\n| Availability | Uptime | 99.9% |\n| Security | Authentication | OAuth 2.0 |\n| Scalability | Concurrent users | 10,000 |\n| Compatibility | Platforms | Linux, macOS |\n\n### 7. Scope Boundaries\n\n**In Scope:**\n- What this PRD covers\n\n**Out of Scope:**\n- What is explicitly excluded\n- What belongs to other PRDs / phases\n\n### 8. Acceptance Criteria\n\nFor each major feature area, define acceptance criteria:\n\n```\nFeature: [name]\n  AC-1: Given ... When ... Then ...\n  AC-2: Given ... When ... Then ...\n```\n\n### 9. Dependencies \u0026 Assumptions\n\n- External service dependencies\n- Team / resource dependencies\n- Assumptions that could affect requirements\n\n### 10. Open Questions\n\nTrack unresolved decisions:\n\n| # | Question | Owner | Status | Decision |\n|---|----------|-------|--------|----------|\n| 1 | ... | ... | Open | ... |\n\n## Quality Criteria\n\n- [ ] Every requirement has a priority (Must/Should/Could/Won't)\n- [ ] Core concepts are defined before being used\n- [ ] User stories follow the standard format\n- [ ] Acceptance criteria are testable (no vague language)\n- [ ] No implementation details (those belong in Spec)\n- [ ] Non-functional requirements have measurable targets\n- [ ] Open questions are tracked with owners\n\n## Style Guidelines\n\n- Requirements use \"shall\" (must), \"should\", \"may\" (could) per MoSCoW\n- One requirement per ID — no compound statements\n- Use concrete examples over abstract descriptions\n- Tables for structured data, prose for narratives\n- Use `$ENV_VAR` placeholders for sensitive values\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. Read BRD (if exists) to understand business context\n2. Gather context from codebase, existing docs, user input\n3. Ask clarifying questions for ambiguous requirements\n4. Generate PRD following the structure above\n5. Write to `docs/prd.md` (or path specified by user)\n6. Highlight open questions and ask for review\n",
