              "content": "---\nname: write-spec\ndescription: Generate a Technical Specification document for a system or feature. Covers architecture, data model, API design, security, and CI/CD with implementation-level detail.\nuser-invocable: true\nargument-hint: [project-name-or-description]\nallowed-tools: Read, Grep, Glob, Bash, Write, Edit\n---\n\n# Write Spec (Technical Specification)\n\nGenerate a structured technical specification for the system described in `$ARGUMENTS`.\n\nIf `$ARGUMENTS` is empty, ask the user to describe the system. If a file path is provided, read it for context. If BRD/PRD exist, reference them.\n\n## What is a Spec\n\nSpec = Technical Specification. It answers **\"How do we build it?\"** at a design level. It translates product requirements (PRD) into architecture decisions, data models, APIs, and engineering constraints.\n\n```\nBRD (Why) → PRD (What) → Spec (How) → Plan (When)\n```\n\n## Document Structure\n\n### 1. Overview\n\n- System / component name\n- One-paragraph technical summary\n- Links to BRD / PRD (if exist)\n- Key architectural decision: why this approach over alternatives\n\n### 2. Core Concepts\n\nMap PRD domain concepts to technical entities:\n\n```\nPRD Concept → Technical Entity\n  Skill      → Directory + SKILL.md + auxiliary files\n  Repository → Git repo with Makefile-based toolchain\n```\n\nFor each entity:\n- Technical definition\n- Storage / representation format\n- Invariants and constraints\n\n### 3. Architecture\n\n#### System Diagram\n\n```\n[Component A] --protocol--\u003e [Component B]\n       |                          |\n       v                          v\n  [Storage A]              [Storage B]\n```\n\n#### Component Breakdown\n\nFor each component:\n- Responsibility (single sentence)\n- Inputs / outputs\n- Dependencies\n- Key interfaces\n\n#### Key Design Decisions\n\n| Decision | Chosen | Alternatives Considered | Rationale |\n|----------|--------|------------------------|-----------|\n| ... | ... | ... | ... |\n\n### 4. Data Model\n\n#### Entities \u0026 Schema\n\n```\nEntity: [Name]\n  field_a: type        -- description\n  field_b: type        -- constraint: unique, regex, etc.\n```\n\n#### State Machines (if applicable)\n\n```\n[State A] --trigger--\u003e [State B] --trigger--\u003e [State C]\n              |\n              +-- guard: condition\n```\n\n#### Validation Rules\n\n| Field | Constraint | Error |\n|-------|-----------|-------|\n| name | `[a-z0-9-]+`, max 64 chars | \"Invalid name format\" |\n| description | non-empty, max 1024 chars | \"Description required\" |\n\n### 5. API / Interface Design\n\n#### Public API\n\n```\nfunction_name(param: Type): ReturnType\n  -- Description\n  -- Throws: ErrorType when condition\n```\n\n#### File Format (if applicable)\n\n```yaml\n---\nrequired_field: type    # description\noptional_field: type    # default: value\n---\nContent body (Markdown)\n```\n\n#### CLI / Makefile Targets (if applicable)\n\n| Target | Description | Example |\n|--------|------------|---------|\n| `make install` | Install to target directory | `make install DEST=~/.cursor/skills` |\n| `make validate` | Run format checks | `make validate` |\n\n### 6. Security \u0026 Sensitivity\n\n#### Threat Model\n\n| Threat | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|--------|-----------|--------|------------|\n| Secret leak in content | Medium | High | CI regex scan + .gitignore |\n\n#### Defense Layers\n\n```\nL1: Access control (repo permissions)\n  ↓\nL2: Content policy (CONTRIBUTING.md rules)\n  ↓\nL3: Automated scanning (CI validation)\n```\n\n#### Prohibited Patterns\n\n- Hardcoded secrets (API keys, private keys, passwords)\n- Internal IPs / domains (use `$ENV_VAR` placeholders)\n- Customer / production data in examples\n\n### 7. CI / Automation\n\n#### Validation Pipeline\n\n```\nPR opened → validate.sh → [pass/fail] → review → merge\n```\n\n#### Validation Rules\n\n| Rule | Severity | Description |\n|------|----------|-------------|\n| SKILL.md